text:
this article by @drninashapiro is on point! i read it last night and just had to comment because it reminded me so much of my training. this is me, during my plastic surgery residency. i was the only female in three graduating classes, and i couldn‚Äôt have asked for a better experience üíô
.
in the era of the #metoo movement, i wanted to share my experience of being a female in surgery.  it really can‚Äôt get more male-dominated than that. thinking back on 4 years of medical school, 5 years of general surgery training, and 3 years of plastic surgery training, i‚Äôm grateful to have nothing but positive experiences. i was respected, treated equally, and my opinion was valued. yes, our attendings were tough on us, but they were tough on all of us. they pushed us to reach our potential and made us stronger and better surgeons so we could take the best care of our patients. these men are my mentors and friends. the people i call when i need help or advice or just a friendly boost of encouragement.
.
pictured here are my co-residents, my ride or die. they are amazing plastic surgeons and people. i‚Äôd trust them with anything.
.
the #metoomovement is real and i suppose i was lucky enough to never have faced this when it came to male superiors and peers. i wanted to share my story because, oftentimes, the positive ones are never told.
.
the sad part of it all is most of the negative encounters i had were with other women. there have been countless incidents spanning from residency to this day, as an attending surgeon. with all of the issues we face as a gender, we need to stick together and support one another. when we find women who do that, we need to hold on.
.
read this article, it won‚Äôt disappoint. there‚Äôs a twist in there. link in bio.
.

.‚Å£

text:
shame on you @goldenglobes @fijiwater . seriously? 
all this "fiji girl steals the show at golden globes" and a thousand stories and posts about her photobombing celebrities , really? this is a total pr fail and all you media covering this should be mortified for missing an epic opportunity to raise awareness about the tragic plastic pollution crisis happening.

fiji water is part of an industry built on extreme wastefulness and manufactured demand ‚Äî one leaving a potentially devastating global ecological trail. it's just another contributor to the great throw away plastic culture we live in. 
this event showed a very disappointing failure to grasp the mood in california where plastic pollution is a severe issue in the legislature and in media. plastic bottles and straws are top offenders on the beach and are consistently among the top 10 items found on coastal cleanup day.

what would have been awesome and worth reporting- celebrities speaking up about this ridiculous , and insulting stunt. how can we all be so #metoo and just not even flinch at this injustice? where are all my favorite positive , renegade environmental celebs? please speak up, use your platform. our kids deserve better . 
i would love someone in the industry  to please  commit to launch a pledge to say no to having plastic at future award shows. and editors, reporters, media platforms , you are as guilty as the organizers for giving attention to this . #saynotosingleuseplastics #plasticfree @healthebay @plasticpollutes @surfriderla

text: we kicked off 2019 with some challenging fun, working on venus by #suzanloriparks for stc‚Äôs rediscovery series, directed by #natsuonodapower. i‚Äôve loved slp‚Äôs work since i was introduced to topdog/underdog in high school & learned that she was a student of hero, #jamesbaldwin. when asked to do the reading, i was reminded that i still hadn‚Äôt read venus, the fictional life story of #sarahbaartman. reading it & then working on it with this talented team was a gift for many reasons. the main gift was an opportunity to process very layered thoughts & feelings about the exploitation, abuse, & objectification of the black body. this play is a timely challenge for us all to be more vigilant & vocal in the face of these social ills that have been ingrained in our cultures worldwide for centuries. grateful for the fuel to our fire to fight against & end rampant sexist, racist, predatory attacks of all kinds. #timesup #blacklivesmatter #metoo #survivors #intersectionality #art #artivism #ally #history #herstory

text: finding yourself after trauma, coping and hiding is a journey that‚Äôs long, scary and exhausting. so many are doing it with a smile and a mindset of ‚Äúfake it til you make it.‚Äù well, sometimes that doesn‚Äôt work. you‚Äôre trying so hard to convince yourself and trying even harder to convince others that you‚Äôre good, happy. give yourself a break love, it‚Äôs okay to feel not okay. okay? you can feel hurt, angry, disappointed and lonely. just know that those feelings are just as fleeting as unplanned out new years resolutions. you can do this, you will find the beautiful inside that wants nothing more but to embrace your flaws, kiss your scars and protect your weaknesses. you‚Äôve made it love, another sixty seconds. don‚Äôt hold back and be compassionate to yourself, forgive yourself. eventually you‚Äôll learn to love yourself and soon you‚Äôll even prefer your own company before you waste your precious time with those negative thoughts that tried to keep you captive. #recovery #surviving #onemorestep #metoo #itsokay #noncaptivi #wading #majordepressionandanxiety #bipolar #iambeauty #unstoppable #thatonefriend #mentalhealth

text:
exhibition highlight! sideshow by @leandraurrutia and @hfwetzel is an interactive installation piece with magic boxes - a deceptive puzzle that can be opened from two directions, revealing the contents of only one side at a time. want to know what‚Äôs in the other box? come to the exhibit & find out. on view now with a reception on jan. 25!

artists' statement: "women's voices and standpoints continue to be viewed as sideshow material. instead of being taken seriously, the agency of women with the courage to expose the character flaws and misdeeds of powerful men has been reduced to fodder that bemuses and entertains. large bank accounts work their magic so that the public finds it hard to discern truth from lies, muddying the waters when proof of dishonesty and nefarious acts surface. trickery becomes unavoidable when reality does not align with the beliefs and positions of the despicable." #metoo #mcaexhibition #enough #installationart

text:
read the full article on @elephantjournal ‚ù§Ô∏è. if our partner behaves in a way that causes us pain, like mine did when he stonewalled me after our child‚Äôs death, oxytocin responds in ways that someone in a safe, romantic relationship would not experience.

when it comes to the brain, context is everything. what happens around you affects your neurochemistry, and this, in turn, affects the entire system of the body. the hormones released in the brain affect the total ecosystem of the body.

these effects lead to two psychological states for the partners of individuals who are emotionally abusive. both of the two psychological states override proper reasoning that could help them gain freedom from their toxic relationship. these psychological states are known as cognitive dissonance and trauma bonding.

text:
[4/5] the rest of my high school years were mostly a blur. after graduating, i began studying at parsons school of design in nyc where i was able to explore my love for fashion and textiles. as many other women do, i buried my experiences with sexual assault and tried to ‚Äúmove on‚Äù with my life without having undergone a formal healing process. at college i was in my element & being around other creative people really helped to bring me out of my shell. while i was a student, i fell in love with makeup and used it's magic to transform the way i felt about myself, it became my armor - a shield. however, underneath my mask, there was still a storm raging. i was anxiety-ridden, developed a pattern of continuing to date toxic men, and was easily angered. one thing that i realize now that i am able to look back is that being molested takes away your sense of self-worth & your expectations of men. when your first sexual experience is through coercive control at such a delicate age, your sense of what is and isn‚Äôt acceptable in relationships becomes warped. as a college student, i hadn‚Äôt realized that i deserved a loving and supportive partner who i could rely on and it‚Äôs taken many years to shed the layers of self-loathing and become the person that i am today. graduating parsons was a huge step in my journey and completing my degree helped give me a sense of confidence. the pain simmered after i graduated, but never fully faded and i put myself in survival mode by becoming a workaholic and partying heavily, hoping it would help me avoid my true feelings. i got married at 27 & began a new chapter overseas, and that's when life threw more devastation my way. in 2004, i gave birth to my daughter but ended up losing her - the experience shattered me and broke me into a million little pieces. i became numb and it felt impossible to go on. somehow, i was able to find strength and took small steps into trying to regain balance in my life. in 2005, i got divorced and headed back to the us with no choice but to deal with the weight of my experiences, it was then that i decided to begin my healing journey and to start kc makeup.
‚úçüèº @pri_pards

text:
i remember some years ago before i even went natural, i met a lady who had really long hair. i asked her how she maintained it and what products she used.... she said she used just 4 staple products : water, shea butter, coconut oil and black soap. .
true talk! .
i was wowed. unfortunately we get carried away by the truckload of products in the market and we want to try them all.... .
just find what works for you and stick to it. like i always say... learn to listen to your hair. that'll save you a lot of money and stress. üëç

text:
üö®warning: long post aheadüö®i wrote this in 2017 right after i watched the first season of #13reasonswhy clearly i was triggered alot. i wanted to share my truth so many times and especially for the take back the night event my school was hosting that year but i remained silent. now as i‚Äôm writing this i‚Äôm nervous with a golf ball size lump forming in my throat. i just don‚Äôt want to be silent anymore. over the past few years so many women has been ostracized, ridiculed and blamed for sharing their truth. people wondered why they waited so long or why they didn‚Äôt do this or that. the reality is no one plans to be sexually assaulted so when you‚Äôre in that moment you‚Äôre in survival mode and survival might mean you fight until the death, survival might mean you freeze and dissociate, survival might mean you run, if running is an option. then afterwards it‚Äôs still survival: how do i live with this? how do i get through this? i chose to be silent because i believed it was necessary for my survival and i was wrong. for true healing and living, i need to release this fully. so here‚Äôs my truth. 
#metoo #sexualassualt #awareness #survivingrkelly #poetry #poetryismytherapy #iwrite #timesup #truth #healing #wholeness

text:
i used to sit alone during lunch in high school. .
one day i was wearing a skirt in class sitting on the edge of a desk talking to the cool kids. one of the guys was playing with his phone. i didn't know what he was doing, i thought he was just on his phone. the next day almost everyone had a picture of me with my legs open and my underwear showing. 12 hours and i was the school slut. ppl asked me what i was thinking?
.
what did i expect? i sat with myself this morning and looked at myself in the mirror and asked did you know he was taking pictures of you?..i swear i didn't. .
.
after that all i wanted was to get out of high school. guys would hit on me expecting me to sleep with them. expecting me to allow them to touch me. i would just let them. i just wanted to get out. i was the nerdy, quiet girl who was now the freak if you cornered her just the right way.
.
this was way before social media. this was all word of mouth. i can't imagine what it's like being a high schooler now. having someone make statuses and have group chats behind your back. i think we forget what it's like going through high school. how it is a competition. we forget the bad days. i look at the stats of teen depression rates and my heart hurts but i'm not surprised. we have made bullying in rapid time. you can ruin someone's reputation in 1minute.

text:
"my introduction to sex wasn‚Äôt a very nice one. my older brother and i grew up in an extremely abusive household. my stepfather had all these warped ideas and opinions and if you didn‚Äôt conform and agree, you were punished. for example, he would punish my brother for his femininity. i don‚Äôt know if he was gay or if it was just his personality but either way, he was a 10 year old boy who was beginning his personal and sensitive journey of discovering his sexuality. my stepfather would scream and shout at him, demanding him to admit that he was gay. my brother would insist he wasn‚Äôt and then be punished for not admitting it.
-
because we were in a household where abuse and violence was the one consistent thing in our lives, my brother dealt with it in his own abusive way and took it out on me. there are many memories i‚Äôll never forget - his hands holding me down, his threats keeping me silent, his breath on my neck, and the look in his eyes.
-
as a result, i went through my teenage years having countless sexual encounters with men who i never really even wanted touching me because i only ever saw myself as a piece of meat and i did not have the courage to say no. it wasn‚Äôt until the first time i actually smiled during sex that i realized my past experiences were clouding my views. after eight heavy years of abuse, it has taken me about another eight years to heal. but with each smile came another revelation, another breath of fresh air, and another sense of clarity.
-
the emotional journey i‚Äôve experienced after i freed myself from that house is what makes me who i am today. i now know that i‚Äôm not a piece of meat. i‚Äôm not someone‚Äôs validation. i‚Äôm not weak. i‚Äôm not damaged goods. i‚Äôm not worthless. i‚Äôm not alone. the advice i would give to people who have had to re-explore sex in a new and positive way is to remember that if it doesn‚Äôt make you smile, then it isn‚Äôt right. you are in charge of your body, and you can use it as you wish. embrace and love yourself, and always remember to smile."
name: Lets Talk About Sex. For Real.

because we were in a household where abuse and violence was the one consistent thing in our lives, my brother dealt with it in his own abusive way and took it out on me. there are many memories i‚Äôll never forget - his hands holding me down, his threats keeping me silent, his breath on my neck, and the look in his eyes.
-
as a result, i went through my teenage years having countless sexual encounters with men who i never really even wanted touching me because i only ever saw myself as a piece of meat and i did not have the courage to say no. it wasn‚Äôt until the first time i actually smiled during sex that i realized my past experiences were clouding my views. after eight heavy years of abuse, it has taken me about another eight years to heal. but with each smile came another revelation, another breath of fresh air, and another sense of clarity.
-
the emotional journey i‚Äôve experienced after i freed myself from that house is what makes me who i am today. i now know that i‚Äôm not a piece of meat. i‚Äôm not someone‚Äôs validation. i‚Äôm not weak. i‚Äôm not damaged goods. i‚Äôm not wohless. i‚Äôm not alone. the advice i would give to people who have had to re-explore sex in a new and positive way is to remember that if it doesn‚Äôt make you smile, then it isn‚Äôt right. you are in charge of your body, and you can use it as you wish. embrace and love yourself, and always remember to smile."

text:
working on the #strongwoman that started it all... artemisa gentileschi.
i clearly remember being an undergrad at lenoir-rhyne university in my first art history class when i saw her painting of judith beheading holofernes, and being gobstruck by four thoughts:
1. holy cow that painting is crazy powerful!
2. why is this the only female artist we've learned about?
3. where are all the girls?
4. who is artemisia?
her story is beyond powerful and moving. it shook me to my core and woke me up from my privileged ignorance. 
i highly recommend taking a moment to look her up.
i still teach my art students about her every semester.

text:
have you watched #survivingrkelly yet? if you feel able to, please do!

the documentary highlights how as a society we fail black women time and time again. we don‚Äôt socially perceive black girls and women as innocent and we don‚Äôt trust or believe their testimony‚Äôs. this is not only true of the juror who explicitly said he didn‚Äôt believe the victims because of their appearance or how they spoke ‚Äì in other words because they are black.

but, all of us who have ignored these women‚Äôs stories, including the numerous artists who have continued to work with r kelly, need to take a hard look at why we have been willing to pass these women‚Äôs stories off as ‚Äúrumors‚Äù. surviving r kelly also brings to the fore the inextricable link between sex and power. the brave testimony‚Äôs of the survivors highlights how sex can be (and often is) used as a means of dominating. we need to be looking more deeply and more critically at this link so that we can more fully understand sexual abuse, assault and rape.

we absolutely cannot separate r kellys music from his abuse. he has trailers at his video shoots and built bedrooms in his studio where he held and abused underage girls, and then he wrote songs like ‚Äòbump n grind‚Äô, ‚Äòit seems like your ready‚Äô ‚Äòage ain‚Äôt nothing but a number‚Äô these songs are all about abusing girls. this is indeed hiding in plain sight.

men like this feel they are untouchable in part because they are rich. r kelly is able to afford payoffs, lawyers and nda‚Äôs because of the revenue he continually receives from support of his music. he has also been able to hide behind the status he has achieved as an artist (from songs about abusing children). let us stand as allies with these survivors. joining the @officialmuterkelly movement first and foremost, but also really looking at why we do not trust and believe or care fully for black women and girls and woc more widely, and looking at why we are so quick to excuse or ignore womens accounts in favour of shielding men (artists or otherwise) from being held accountable for the abuse.

text:
you know i figured i'd shed this light. i've come to terms with it and accepted it. but back in september in was almost raped cause i invited a guy to come over and hang out. he clearly had a different idea and wouldnt leave me alone when i told him to stop. when i called an old friend of mine to get an excuse to leave. he backed off. however, those people i called my friends? they took me to this safe dating booth when the school had this random festival. their reasoning? "you were coming on really strong to that guy. we wanna make sure you make smart decisions." this is the third time i've been through this situation in ten years. i was wearing my pajamas and asked him if he wanted to hang out and play some card games. clearly me in my sweats and a baggy shirt means i "come on too strong" so yeah. men arent the only people who are trash. women can be shit too.
#metoo #timesup

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn‚Äôs don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan‚Äôs app may not have been completely deleted. kogan‚Äôs app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

#child #sexualabuse üëá üëáüèæ üëáüèø is an issue that makes people extremely uncomfortable, because it hurts to think about anyone harming children. however, unreported or untreated child sexual abuse not only scars children and destroys families, it also leaves offenders free to #abuse and cripple future generations

what is child sexual abuse?

it is any sexual activity between adults and minors or between two minors when one forces it on the other.¬†this includes sexual touching and non-touching acts like exhibitionism, exposure to pornography, photography of a child for sexual gratification, solicitation of a child for prostitution, voyeurism and communication in a sexual way by phone, internet or face-to-face. it is a crime punishable by law that must be reported.

how often does child sexual abuse take place?¬†fact: the real prevalence of child sexual abuse is not known because so many victims do not disclose or report their abuse. researchers have suggested rates varying from 1% to 35%. most professionals in the field of abuse use rates from 8% to 20%.fact: even if the true prevalence of child sexual abuse is not known, most will agree that there will be 500,000 babies born in the us this year that will be sexually abused before they turn 18 if we do not prevent it.adult retrospective studies show that 1 in 4 women and 1 in 6 men were sexually abused before the age of 18 (centers for disease control and prevention, 2006). this means there are more than 42 million adult survivors of child sexual abuse in the u.s.the primary reason that the public is not sufficiently aware of child sexual abuse as a problem is that 73% of child victims do not tell anyone about the abuse for at least a year. 45% of victims do not tell anyone for at least 5 years. some never disclose !  #metoo #protectourkids #speak #ncrediblegang

text:
day 2 of our january deep dive into the post-show workshop! today we're discussing how rehearsing for life is just as important as rehearsing for a show. whether you're a performer or not.

you never thought all those hours in the rehearsal room would pay off when the show ended, huh? well we're here to say that they're well worth it.

life can throw us into some difficult conversations. in today's culture everything we say can have an afterlife online.

no reason to fret! let's rehearse for it.

#powertotheshe #herstory #metoo

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the effos made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to cou documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the cou documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
lawsuit charges donald trump with raping a 13-year-old girl

a civil suit against donald trump alleging he raped a 13-year-old girl was dismissed in california in may 2016, refiled in new york in june 2016, and dropped again in november 2016.

a federal lawsuit filed in new york accuses republican presidential candidate donald trump of repeatedly raping a 13-year-old girl more than 20 years ago, at several upper east side parties hosted by convicted sex offender and notorious billionaire investor jeffrey epstein.
the suit, first reported by the real deal, accuses trump and epstein of luring the anonymous plaintiff and other young women to four parties at epstein‚Äôs so-called wexner mansion at 9 east 71st street. epstein allegedly lured the plaintiff, identified in the suit only as jane doe, with promises of a modeling career and cash.
another anonymous woman, identified in additional testimony as tiffany doe, corroborates jane‚Äôs allegations, testifying that she met epstein at port authority, where he hired her to recruit other young girls for his parties. trump had known epstein for seven years in 1994 when he attended the parties at wexner, according to the suit. he also allegedly knew that the plaintiff was 13 years old.
jane doe filed a similar suit in california in april, under the name katie johnson, also accusing trump and epstein of rape. that suit was dismissed on the grounds of improper paperwork ‚Äî the address affiliated with her name was found to be abandoned. today‚Äôs suit confirms that the plaintiffs are one and the same.

text:
i called my mom. i told her i didn‚Äôt know what to do. i couldn‚Äôt live here anymore. i was losing it, fast. i was living in lansing, mi, scared, lonely, fighting a post-trauma battle that i was losing. i tried searching for help, desperately seeking advice, but my motivation to search continuously lacked. i knew there were resources, but it was much easier to stay at home in bed, in the dark, hiding but not escaping, growing in dangerous ways...üçÇ
‚Ä¢
soon after calling my mom, she came and moved me back to ohio into my family‚Äôs home. i started going to bikram classes again, hot pilates, and eventually joined the ashtanga community in toledo, a routine that would quite literally save my life. i didn‚Äôt think a lot during this time, i just did. i was scared of my mind, of my memories, but eventually found courage to face my thoughts on my mat. i started writing, anything and everything, and even found a purpose here, a way to connect with words i couldn‚Äôt say out loud, another routine that would support me. it didn‚Äôt happen quickly, but eventually my mind became my friend again, and i was grateful for my memories. i met kind people, and found joy in redefining my comfort zone. i moved forward, and i kept moving forward.üçÇ
‚Ä¢
i am not exceedingly brave, or courageous, just a human walking through life. we all have battles, big and small, and we are all capable of facing them. i believe in you; i believe in us. i‚Äôm not sure where my inspiration to share this part of this story comes from today. maybe just to let you know i can be a resource if you need one. maybe to take another step towards plans i have to help others struggling from these acts. maybe to continue moving forward. anyways, no matter your battle, we are stronger together.üçÇ
‚Ä¢

text:
‚Äúthe storm is coming,‚Äù say the conspiracy theorizers whose grotesque imaginings terrified the country to attention this week. maybe they‚Äôre right.

the simplest description of the plot line goes something like this: president trump isn‚Äôt under investigation; he is only pretending to be, as part of a countercoup to restore power to the people after more than a century of governmental control by a globalist cabal. also, there are pedophiles.

a figure named ‚Äúq,‚Äù who supposedly possesses q-level security clearance, disperses ‚Äúcrumbs‚Äù that ‚Äúbakers‚Äù bring together to create a ‚Äúdough‚Äù of synthesized information. (this is not how baking works, but that seems the least of our worries.) because q is the 17th letter in the alphabet and 17 is also a number trump has said a few times, among other clearly-not-coincidences, he is the real deal, not an internet troll engaged in an elaborate example of live-action role-play.

that‚Äôs what qanon followers really want, after all. that‚Äôs where their ‚Äústorm‚Äù motto comes from. most americans were puzzled when, in a meeting with military leaders months ago, trump said, ‚Äúyou know what this represents? maybe it‚Äôs the calm before the storm.‚Äù but these theorists thought they knew exactly what he was talking about. trump was pointing at the officers‚Äô uniforms.

the storm qanon truthers predict will never strike because the conspiracy that obsesses them doesn‚Äôt exist. but while they wait for it, they‚Äôll try to whip up the winds, and the rest of us will struggle to find shelter. qanon is scary because it‚Äôs getting bigger, it‚Äôs scary because we don‚Äôt know how to stop it, and it‚Äôs scary because the people behind it won‚Äôt be stopped, and, until their illusory storm arrives, they won‚Äôt be satisfied.

molly roberts
the washington post

text: so detention centers. death in custody. i don't know exactly what's going on at the border. i can however share what happened in a girls home, i was in, cause they don't want to deal with real problems so they lock people away when we ask for help. no dudes allowed not in an degrading way, but for healing purposes. women can be very scary, also all the women going through their various traumas, everyone was drugged. it wasn't really about healing, as they said in that environment, with that much trauma in a room, it's about surviving and walking on eggshells and glass. not to mention the polarity shift, when everyone had taken their drugs and surviving that. rape and various reasons were why i was there. everyone had their own. i was one of the youngest. there were many girls and women. with prison reform yeah that's important, but custody reform and justice reform, and acknowledging the true colors and violence in our country for base humanity levels is a different priority of importance. anyway. a lady died. she was nice, we ate together sometimes. she was a white lady, a nurse, who had witnessed her husband's suicide and could not save him. they had a son. after the death, he was military or something, the family was to receive govt. survivor funding. i had never heard of that before, and don't understand that concept well. her immediate family, after the death, did the establish dominance and psychologically jumped her for the check and her rights to her son, because the caretaker of the son got the check. they somehow got what they wanted and not long after her husband's suicide, there we were. she was smart, and kind, and i liked talking to her and staying out of the cliques and packs of very scary prison rule, drugged up survivors. she stole a lot of insulin and killed herself. i didn't know, i couldn't be there. the amount counsel and staff you think they would have noticed all the insulin missing. their son has two dead parents. is at the will of people don't care about his or his mom's life, or life at all. this is all very depressing, i don't know if that helps describe what those places are like. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
‚Äúthe storm is coming,‚Äù say the conspiracy theorizers whose grotesque imaginings terrified the country to attention this week. maybe they‚Äôre right.

the simplest description of the plot line goes something like this: president trump isn‚Äôt under investigation; he is only pretending to be, as part of a countercoup to restore power to the people after more than a century of governmental control by a globalist cabal. also, there are pedophiles.

a figure named ‚Äúq,‚Äù who supposedly possesses q-level security clearance, disperses ‚Äúcrumbs‚Äù that ‚Äúbakers‚Äù bring together to create a ‚Äúdough‚Äù of synthesized information. (this is not how baking works, but that seems the least of our worries.) because q is the 17th letter in the alphabet and 17 is also a number trump has said a few times, among other clearly-not-coincidences, he is the real deal, not an internet troll engaged in an elaborate example of live-action role-play.

that‚Äôs what qanon followers really want, after all. that‚Äôs where their ‚Äústorm‚Äù motto comes from. most americans were puzzled when, in a meeting with military leaders months ago, trump said, ‚Äúyou know what this represents? maybe it‚Äôs the calm before the storm.‚Äù but these theorists thought they knew exactly what he was talking about. trump was pointing at the officers‚Äô uniforms.

the storm qanon truthers predict will never strike because the conspiracy that obsesses them doesn‚Äôt exist. but while they wait for it, they‚Äôll try to whip up the winds, and the rest of us will struggle to find shelter. qanon is scary because it‚Äôs getting bigger, it‚Äôs scary because we don‚Äôt know how to stop it, and it‚Äôs scary because the people behind it won‚Äôt be stopped, and, until their illusory storm arrives, they won‚Äôt be satisfied.

molly roberts
the washington post

text:
any victim-survivor of abuse can tell you that the psychological and emotional damage takes far longer to heal than physical damage.
some victim-survivors talk about wishing their partner had just punched them in the face instead of slowly poisoning their entire life with years of abuse.
we are not here to say anyone has more/worse pain than anyone else ‚Äî we are here to say all pain is valid and worthy of recognition and justice.

text:
asking for a friend...
.
.
i have this friend.  he‚Äôs one of the smartest people i know and yet he‚Äôs always second guessing himself and his decisions.  at times he can be so sure and so confident and yet there are times when he literally looks like a shell of himself.  he‚Äôs also one of the most caring and kindest individuals i know but i‚Äôve also seen him readily take the blame and shame given to him by others...the kinda blame and shame that‚Äôs not deserved but projected by other people‚Äôs unhappiness.  he‚Äôs crazy talented and super creative but i‚Äôve also watched him play so small and so simple...as if he‚Äôs trying incredibly hard to fit in and stay below the radar.  he‚Äôs a master at hiding but he‚Äôs amazing at encouraging others to stand out.  i have this friend.
.
.
the other day i tell him 2019 is gonna be the year...the year he‚Äôs gonna break free from his past failures, from his negative self-doubt, and from the awful opinions and thoughts of others.  i tell him this is gonna be the year people finally get to hear his songs...the ones he‚Äôs been writing for years...the ones no one ever gets the chance to hear.  i tell him he‚Äôs gonna grow as man, as a father, as a friend, as a human being and that it‚Äôs only gonna better his relationships...all of them.  and then i looked him in the eyes and tell him that he‚Äôs already started this process back in 2018...that now he just needs to finish it in 2019. .
.
don‚Äôt you wish we could make our friends believe in themselves the way we believe in them?  or a better question is...have you ever been this friend?  cuz maybe i have and i‚Äôm just asking...for a friend üòâüíú
.
.
.
.

text: last year i had the opportunity to ask @taranajaneen (civil rights activist and founder of the #metoo movement) about the overlap of sexual harassment / sexual assault and pop culture (music, sports, comedy, etc.) and how she reconciles her feelings. i used r. kelly as a specific example and her response was very simple. she reminded me that when we give people money‚Äî by streaming their music, buying their products, going to their events‚Äî we directly contribute to their bottom line and give them the resources that allow them to continue perpetrating their crimes. i think about this conversation often and wanted to share in the hopes that it might help others understand why #muterkelly is so important.

text:
2018 was pretty rough. i left one dysfunctional job for another, which i quit last month after the owner sexually harassed me. i‚Äôve been dealing with the fallout from that in my own way: sharing the story when i had the energy, and keeping quiet when i was exhausted and spent. some days are better than others, largely thanks to the beautiful people who reached out in the beginning and keep checking in with me (you know who you are üòä). i‚Äôm in the rumble part now: sorting out my story, picking up the pieces, and figuring out where to go from here. what‚Äôs kept me going is that i‚Äôve never strayed from my values of respect and integrity‚Äîi respected myself too much to stay in an untenable situation, and my integrity won‚Äôt let me stay silent when the shame belongs to someone else. i won‚Äôt carry that on my shoulders. thank you also to the women who‚Äôve shared your stories with me. the shocking, but not surprising, thing is, almost every one of you has a story like mine. this should not be. we do not have to suffer in silence, and we will not be shamed for the actions of others. whatever you decide, whether you share your story publicly, with a loved one, with a therapist, or in the privacy of your journal, know that you owe no one your silence. they do not have power over your story. ‚Ä¢

text:
i can't believe i've never seen "the right stuff" until now. i used to build model spaceships as a kid, the last generation of american kids to remember the space program at its zenith, before challenger sapped the public's interest and feckless congress after feckless congress failed to fund the space program without the threat of soviet dominance.
‚ôæ
maybe that will change now? the future of space, which is to say the future of exploring the boundaries and limits of humankind seems more likely to be written by china or private companies than nasa these days and there's a part of myself that says, "that's probably for the best." ‚ôæ
the guys; all guys of course (and there's a freshman tisch film student writing a paper on whether the treatment of women in this film is problematic or not in the #metoo era somewhere right now i'm sure), are old school americans. you can't help but ask in this terribly divided age whether our past heroes were progressives or nationalists, but these guys just believe in an america. and so do all the other americans in the film; the press, the scientists, the rich and poor all believe in it.
‚ôæ
what i think we've discovered in the last few years is that we don't believe in one america anymore. my america is not the country donald trump's supporters live in. this is hard because among those supporters are family. the country now is clearly divided because we now only focus on what we disagree about.
‚ôæ
seems this all turns out one of two ways: we find an america we can all believe in again together as a people or one way or another, we will part ways; houses divided as the saying goes. .
.
.
.
.

text:
i couldn‚Äôt make posting this weekend but boy do i have so much to say. i feel like it‚Äôs been a whirl wind last couple of days. anyway.... from watching the #survingrkelly docuseries to the relevant posts, to other worldly issues, it truly saddens me that people have no empathy. people wonder why so many people don‚Äôt speak up about abuse & topics of that nature. this is why. the backlash, fear of backlash! not being trusted, not being believed & reliving the trauma through such legal battles that are just as bad as the experience itself without the name calling & negative connotations. it‚Äôs sick ! it makes my stomach turn, it‚Äôs disgusting that it even exist, yet there are people making excuses for it. lacking such compassion or  empathy that they justify any such grooming or abuse. i‚Äôm sad to be a part of such humanity at times like this. this should open our eyes to simply do better, to love more & unconditionally. period. people who disagree don‚Äôt @ me idgaf
.
.
we‚Äôve just got to do sooo much better ! towards ourselves, one another and our communities. people, women, girls are already afraid, feeling helpless, hopeless, unworthy & sick to their stomach with guilt & shame !! this will also include some boys & men ! all of which was created by someone else. you think they‚Äôre all thinking about themselves !? no !!? they have soo much more they think about including the ‚Äúwho‚Äôs going to believe me? who can i tell ? who can i go to ? where, how ? but ?‚Äù. it‚Äôs not right that people are first quick to defend the unjust, wrong & corrupt before the innocent, vulnerable ones. if you can‚Äôt understand or rationalise these type of messages don‚Äôt say anything, don‚Äôt comment negative things to the victims, don‚Äôt share your negative opinions about the abused. groomers, abusers, child molesters, rapists & any such predictors alike take many forms, shapes, ‚Äúrole model‚Äù & sizes. don‚Äôt be ignorant, his music alone is all the evidence needed. a fourteen to fifteen year old is just reaching teenagehood & they are vulnerable adolescents. they are easily misguided, manipulated, forced into situations & mislead. period. we should be doing more to identify the sick individuals...cont‚Äôdüëá

text:
i care about your parenting. not because i want to sit on my high horse to judge it, not at all. i care because those children will grow up to be partners, parents, employees, employers, leaders, change agents, etc. who they grow up to be matters. every person today who brought a gun into a school taking innocent lives, sexually assaulted another human, physically or emotionally abused their children or partner, every single one of them used to be a child. they were someone‚Äôs baby. how we parent and raise our children matters.
‚Ä¢
seed & sew was created to establish the modern parenting village because ‚Äúi turned out okay‚Äù is not a valid excuse for repeating negative behaviors. when we know better, we can do better, and we know more about tiny human brains than ever before, so let‚Äôs walk the walk.
‚Ä¢

happy new year. time is an abstract and humanity is just one big game of telephone. we try to interpret the past but filter it through our own assumptions, resulting in garbled but firm announcements of "truth". i practice constant humility and do my best to check myself, my facts, and my privilege at all times. that being said, it's time to speak up and call people out! 2019 will see no more of my polite silence! abuse and inequality have been socially programmed as acceptable, and need to be rewritten and brought to light. i will no longer concern myself with being polite in the face of (primarily, through just my experience) misogyny and the little sexist acts and comments that pepper everyday life. i've been better at standing up for other people than myself, when it comes to real life real time abuse. that won't change, but i'm gonna make sure to stand up for myself now, too. fuck that shit. no chill. let's go.

tldr; abuse can happen in same-sex relationships and it appears that its prevalence is similar (or higher) than opposite-sex couples. and it isn‚Äôt easier for lgbt+ survivors to leave the relationship for a myriad of factors (ex. outing themselves, lack of support, etc). because of the heavy‚Äîheavy‚Äîemphasis on heterosexual relationships where the female is the victim and the male is the abuser, people in different situations are not given the same resources as straight women victims. this looks like a lack of men‚Äôs shelters, people not believing you, a lack of help lines to call, having little support, etc. it‚Äôs 2019, recognizing that abuse can happen regardless of the type of relationship and gender of the abuser is the first step to reduce the stigma around these victims and to start offering them resources to help escape these abusive situations.

text:
"we cannot change the cards we were dealt, just how we play the game."
this quote speaks volumes to me. triggers have been hitting me in the face over and over again recently and i have not been handling it the way i would like to be. because of the way i was treated growing up, my default coping mechanisms are always to self destruct and it has taken so much out of me and has taken a toll on both my mental and physical health. after a much needed session with my amazing therapist tonight, i realized that my body and my brain cannot take much more of my own mistreatment towards myself, especially after the many years of abuse that was inflicted on it by others. it is literally killing me. but i am going to work on getting myself back on track with my recovery and right now my main focus will be on self care, because that is one area i have been majorly slacking in. life has been chaotic, but i am so grateful for those who have stood by my side through it all - like my sisters, my brother in law, my boyfriend, my closest friends, my treatment team, and without their knowledge, even my nieces have been a major help to me. they have put up with so much from me and i will forever be thankful for that. i could not have made it this far in life without them.
#eatingdisorderrecovery #ptsdrecovery #eatingdisorderawareness #ptsdawareness #mentalhealthawareness #anorexiarecovery #bulimiarecovery #suicideawareness #suicidesurvivor #mentalhealthmatters #neda #sexualabuse #nami #freedom #traumasurvivor #cptsd #metoo #traumarecovery #followers #recoveryisworthit #recoveryispossible #fighter #followme #follow #survivor #speakyourtruth #useyourvoice #stigmafighter #abusesurvivors #sexualassaultsurvivors

text: to be so alive and awake and be privileged to lay right underneath these sacred ‚Äúteo flyers‚Äù on our way to the pyramids was life changing. to witness a ritual so close and to dream into the intent of the elements and four directions washed away my illusion of the world as i knew it.  it became evident that there are ancestors and masters so alive that are all around me making sure i stay focused on integrity and my intent in this life.  i have to live from my heart and speak in alignment with who i really am.  my life is so different than even 2 years ago when i was sent back to fulfill my mission.  i am pure at heart and being sober is an important piece for me.  i am not toxic to myself and aspire not to spread anything but love and light in this world.  witnessing these voladores helped me to realize that being in service from my heart is key in my life.  danza de los voladores or ‚Äúdance of the flyers‚Äù is a mesoamerican ritual still performed today.  the voladores or dancers climb a 30 meter pole with one playing the flute and drum. they launch themselves backwards secured by ropes beginning with the east as this is the direction that life comes from.  the four directions are represented by the 4 voladores as well as the gods of the earth, air, fire and water.  each rope is twisted and each flyer circles the pole 13 times each for a total of 52 circuits, or the total number of years in the ‚Äúaztec calendar round.‚Äù allow this ritual to touch your heart and clear your spirit, lay down and fly like an eagle.  #theshamelesswarrior #metooneveryou #teotihuacan #toltec #dreamingheaven #teotihuacanpyramids #recoveryispossible #sobrietyismylove #sobriety #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #metoo #timesup

text:
entertainment | rape charge against alok nath false:court

details: a court in mumbai yesterday found alok nath might have been falsely implicated by vinta nanda of raping her 19 years ago as she did not remember the date and month of the incident.

the #metoo campaign of india got a big jolt as the court granted anticipatory bail.

the court observed that vinta nanda ‚Äúdid not lodge the report immediately after the alleged incident for her own benefit‚Äù. the court has also observed that ‚Äúpossibility cannot be ruled out that the applicant [alok nath] has been falsely accused in the crime‚Äù. nanda had accused actor alok nath of raping her 19 years ago. nanda did not file a case against nath then as she was told that since alok nath is a big actor, no one would believe her story.

the sessions court observed that there is ‚Äúno record to show that nath had given any threat or made any promise against lodging a report‚Äù. the court has taken into consideration the arguments made by nath‚Äôs lawyer that there were many discrepancies in the complaint that nanda filed.

the court noted that nanda ‚Äúremembers the entire incident but she did not remember the date and month of the incident‚Äù. therefore, the court concluded that there was a ‚Äúpossibility that alok nath was being falsely accused of the crime‚Äù. #rapecharge #indianews #aloknath #mumbai #vintananda #pratidintime

finally watched the docuseries and am literally at a total loss for words. because i speak publicly on behalf of #metoo, #timesup in support of women whom have been violated on so many different levels (and some of you have asked for my opinion), i'd love to share my thoughts in a more in-depth format and not just 5 -minute tv segment; but i first have to wrap my head and heart around what i've seen. and i have so many questions.
***
i've seen a lot of posts from men saying it's a waste of time to watch because we all know. but, no, not really. the sex tape is only part and parcel the demon living in this man. i was a huge fan. i didn't know 1/2 the stuff. did you? there's value in watching in living color the recounts of survivors so that men and women understand and hopefully feel it too in order to help protect our girls, especially our brown and black girls as well as our communities-at-large from these kinds of people. it's not enough to "know" about it. not in this day in age when the internet allows access to anyone and anything.

text:
he looks deep into the lines of his own face,
through digital pathways - and mirrors of expression,
that allow him to hide what he feels from the rest of the world,
nobody knows who he is, where he‚Äôs from, or what he‚Äôs made of,
but he is there - but he is here - simultaneously here and there,
staring into the abyss at last - and as he writes the words,
that will defiantly define his existence,
precious minutes will pass... precious minutes will pass outside his door,
because nobody seems to knock anymore. -

name: The Poetry of Nicholas Jones
tweet_full:
he looks deep into the lines of his own face,
through digital pathways - and mirrors of expression,
that allow him to hide what he feels from the rest of the world,
nobody knows who he is, where he‚Äôs from, or what he‚Äôs made of,
but he is there - but he is here - simultaneously here and there,
staring into the abyss at last - and as he writes the words,
that will defiantly define his existence,
precious minutes will pass... precious minutes will pass outside his door,
because nobody seems to knock anymore. -

text:
"if there's one thing these six hours have taught us, it's that culturally we have failed black women and girls."@thegrio

so how can we stop failing them?
join us tomorrow at 9pm est. 
our panelist includes:

moderator, @daniellecarindunn author of the ivylocs book series.

teresa baker, political consultant, author of josie's bedazzled shoes and ceo/founder of @brownboybrowngirl their mission is to empower and inspire brown boys and brown girls through reading while helping parents to raise children who see the beauty of their true selves.

christopher everage edgar-smith, llmsw, clinical therapist specializing in addiction treatment with a trauma-focused lense.

@yusefbunchyshakur author of the window 2 my soul, my soul looks back and scribes of redemption. a neighborhood organizer, activist, social entrepreneur and documentary filmmaker, shakur is co-director of programs at the michigan roundtable for diversity and inclusion.
.

text: today i was told that the crown prosecutor has decided not to try my case. there will be no charges filed. my assault isn‚Äôt violent enough to warrant serious charges. he is free. i am not safe. they are aware of 3 other woman he has raped and no one cares. despite all of this i am looking for ways to be strong. to figure out what comes next, how i can process this and move on. how do i accept such injustice and recklessness. how do i accept that he will continue to assault woman and no one can stop him. how do i accept that i can no longer go to my home town and feel safe. every day is a battle and now it feels like it was all for nothing. his freedom is worth more then my pain in their eyes. i will be meeting with the prosecutor myself. i want her to look me in the eyes and tell me my assault wasn‚Äôt violent enough. that him holding me down while i begged him to stop and said no until i passed out wasn‚Äôt violent enough. i want her to know i am not a case number i am a human being and if everyone just accepts that there‚Äôs nothing they can do and this is the way it is nothing will change. i am proud of myself for my courage and bravery in coming forward in the first place and suffering through all of this. i just wish it were enough. because it should be. #metoo #injustice #survivor #fighting #nevereasy

text:
[kilas balik pre-event 16 film festival bali 2018]

eksperimen sosial: respons publik terhadap penyintas kekerasan seksual.

pada minggu pagi, 25 november 2018 bertepatan dengan car free day renon, dua orang relawan 16 film festival bali 2018 berdiri dalam krumunan orang-orang dengan mengalungi label "saya korban kekerasan seksual. tolong jabat tangan saya" untuk melihat empati masyarakat terhadap penyintas dan kasus kekerasan seksual secara umum.

ada beragam respons yang didapat para relawan. beberapa ada yang menjabat dan memberi dukungan untuk tetap semangat dan kuat. beberapa juga ada yang memfoto dan merekam korban tanpa menghampirinya. beberapa lainnya jalan begitu saja.

silakan saksikan video eksperimen sosial yang dipersembahkan oleh 16 film festival bali 2018!

@gshrudayana @kisara_bali @lbh_bali

#gshrudayana #genderstudies #sexualitystudies #humanrightsstudies #bali #hearmetoo #metoo #gerakbersama #hapuskekerasanseksual #enambelasffest #enambelasffestbali

text:
[kilas balik 16 film festival bali 2018]

10 desember 2018.

closing night diadakan pada senin, 10 desember 2018 di cushcush gallery pukul 16:00 wita.

kegiatan diawali dengan kata sambutan oleh ketua gshr udayana (@shutuprick) dan direktur ylbhi-lbh bali. kemudian dilanjutkan dengan pemutaran film "siti" (2014) karya eddie cahyono.

setelah pemutaran film berakhir, kegiatan dilanjutkan dengan penampilan akustik oleh sandrayati fay (@sandrayatifay ). kegiatan diakhiri dengan penampilan teatrikal oleh teater kalangan (@teaterkalangan). sekian kilas balik 16 film festival bali 2018. sampai jumpa lagi di kesempatn selanjutnya!

@gshrudayana @kisara_bali @lbh_bali

#gshrudayana #genderstudies #sexualitystudies #humanrightsstudies #bali #hearmetoo #metoo #gerakbersama #hapuskekerasanseksual #enambelasffest #enambelasffestbali

text:
in 2014, steve bannon ‚Äì then executive chairman of the ‚Äúalt-right‚Äù news network breitbart ‚Äì was christopher wylie‚Äôs boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica‚Äôs investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology ‚Äì ‚Äúinformation operations‚Äù ‚Äì then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it‚Äôs insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it‚Äôs like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text: i just finished watching surviving r kelly. it literally took so much out of me and i was in complete disgust. its sad to see that these women still say things like "i consented but i felt pressured". thats not consent. do not blame yourself if you are in an abusive relationship no matter who its with. rape is just that. even if its being done to you by your bf/husband/friend/stranger. having had been in an abusive relationship for years, this hit so close to home. its sad that in this day and age there are still so many ppl that witness your abuse first hand and literally do nothing. why? because its easier to blame you & turn a blind eye than to enrage a monster. it took a lot to not break down but i thank my husband for helping me get through all that hurt & pain that once was my life. no one deserves to be abused physically/mentally or both. know you are worth so much more. if anyone needs to talk, feel free to msg me. i know how hard it is to talk to ppl that dont understand what you feel. the worst thing you can hear is "why didnt you walk away". well whatever your reason, its never too late. #muterkelly #metoo #metoomovement

text:
life and death are in the power of the tongue and they that love it shall eat the fruit of it ; proverbs 18:21. many years ago when i was in university i had a friend who was my room mate and he used to say a phrase that used to get on my every single nerve. he said it especially when i was upset with him or had a disagreement or even when i knew he could not afford something. he would say "because i am rich" . when i am angry with him he would say "you hate me because i am rich" . he he wanted something he could not afford he would say " i will get it because i am rich". well i did not know he was speaking life into his future finances. well in 2014 i saw in church and we sat next to each other. and when it was time for offerings and tithe, i pulled out money from my wallet while brought out his cheque book . i took a peek on what he wrote down . it was 2million naira . it was just god that held my mouth from screaming and embarrassing my self that day. 
it later on i realized his words built the reality of his life. so speak what you want to see in every area of your life , your money, your children ,your spiritual life, your country, your family , your job or business, your friends , your spouse etc and water them with your prayers. then see what god will do for you and how your life will be. speak life and god bless you as you do so. one god ,one love one way. be great and be blessed.
#godislove #godlovesyou #men #women #itstartswithyou #itstartswithus #digits1024 #godisnotdead #inspirenaija #motivatenaija #metoo #speaklife #kingdomman #man #woman #christlike #digits1024 #bellanaijastyle #better #godisgood #godisnotdead #thepoweroflove #thepowerofgodsword #thepowerofgod #heisresin #tumbisempty #iamachristian #akingandapriest #tobymac

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

„Éª„Éª„Éª
keberanian rizky amelia, pegawai badan penyelenggara jaminan sosial (bpjs) ketenagakerjaan, mengungkap pemerkosaan dan perundungan seksual yang menimpanya berkalikali dalam dua tahun terakhir harus didukung. apa yang dilakukan perempuan 27 tahun ini sungguh tak mudah, mengingat terduga pelaku adalah atasannya sendiri, anggotadewan pengawas bpjs ketenagakerjaan, syafri adnan baharuddin, dan kantor tempatnya bekerja seolah olah menutup mata.
.
.
keberanian amel begitu dia biasa disapa muncul seiring dengan era baru ketika perempuan korban kekerasan seksual di seluruh dunia menolak untuk terus dibungkam. selama ini, dengan dalih takut kehilangan pekerjaan atau akses finansial, mereka cenderung diam dan pasrah menjadi korban perundungan seksual. kini tidak lagi.
.
.
gerakan global yang disebut sebagai #metoo atau "saya juga" ini berawal dari pengungkapan kasuskasus perundungan seksual yang dilakukan para pembesar dan selebritas hollywood di amerika serikat pada oktober 2017. dari produser film harvey weinstein, aktor gaek bill cosby, sampai komedian louis c.k. harus kehilangan posisi dan pekerjaan setelah perilaku miring mereka diekspos para korban. gerakan #metoo menginspirasi banyak korban untuk mulai berbicara dengan terbuka mengenai kekerasan seksual yang mereka alami.
.
.

text: i knew who this man was the moment i found out that he married aaliyah. i was in elementary school. at the time i didnt even think about the sex, i just knew it was wrong for a grown man to be married to a child. how is it that all of these adults willingly assisted him in his crimes? they all knew he was sick, and that what was going on was wrong. they still continued business as usual. this went on before aaliyah and is still going on well after shes been gone. i will always considered @missymisdemeanorelliott and @timbaland to be her angles who helped  guide her to become the superstar she was born to be. i did not support him. i never bought any of his albums or even listened to his music willing. i'm not gonna lie; we did have to perform " i believe i can fly" in 4th grade. space jam and michael jordan was the movie and hero of our generation. it is so unfortunate that he is connected to that sweet memory. guaranteed if aalyiah or any of the girls who came before her, or after her were white this would've stopped right then and there. i'm so angry with myself that i wasn't louder with my feelings, because my silent protest helped no one. please bring justice for these poor girls and women who's lives have been destroyed. if there is anyone out there to help guide me and point me in the right direction to help, please let me know. i don't know how to be an activist, but i'm gonna try my best. sign the petition. hit the link in my bio ‚òùÔ∏èüèΩ #muterkelly #timesup #mutethemonster #metoo #blackgirlsmatter #blacklivesmatter

many survivors are too hypervigilant to enjoy the ordinary pleasures that life has to offer, while others are too numb to absorb new experiences ‚Äî or to be alert to signs of real danger.

someone with ptsd may need to talk about the traumatic event over and over again. this is part of the healing process, so avoid the temptation to tell your loved one to stop rehashing the past and move on. instead, offer to talk, as many times as needed. and remember, it's okay to dislike what you hear. some of the things your loved one tells you might be very hard to listen to. but it's important to respect their feelings and reactions, if you come across as disapproving, horrified, or judgemental, they may likely not open up to you again.

one thing i know for sure is that hurt people, hurt people. as a victim of abuse i don‚Äôt have to create a space of compassion for abusers. they too must access their own healing the same way their victims have to.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.
