text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text: i spent the better part of this morning reading about the harvey weinstein and it dawned on me how sometimes right and wrong, the light and darkness in man, can be so difficult to separate and how it‚Äôs in our human nature for some unexplainable reason to flirt with both until the edge of chaos. harvey is a sexual predator and for decades those around him knew it, his staff, his partners, confidants, and even the victims before they were victims, all knew of his demonic side. even his attorneys who controlled witnesses through ndas knew this man was a monster. yet for over two decades, everyone let it play out. it‚Äôs just incredible to me that something so black and white could go unchecked for so long. why is it that when facing blatant injustices, sometimes we simply turn away? and then you are left wondering further, what other clear and obvious injustices am i now too baring witness to that still have yet to be rightened? flint comes to mind. we people are so powerful yet sometimes it really takes earthshaking, watershed moments like the #metoo movement to get us all working in synchronicity for good. we need more courageous women and men to reject evil and protect good. i know it‚Äôs a very general statement but it‚Äôs not as easy in practice to understand. i hope harvey gets to spend the rest of his life behind bars thinking about the pain he caused people and i hope those people who stood by him while he did these atrocities find the courage to stand up to other wrongdoings in the future, unwaveringly.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
are past memories / emotional traumas holding you back?  are you experiencing anxiety type symptoms such as impaired sleep, a feeling of heaviness on the chest, muscle tension, upset stomach, feelings of hopelessness or anger?

during chromotherapy sessions, we often start with the furthest most traumatic event / emotional trauma.  this allows us to also address other smaller traumas / events that are linked to the original trauma.  at the end of a session, it is common to feel a sense of relief and a feeling of neutrality associated with the past traumatic event.  the best part is that follow-ups are very rare!

text:
officially introducing my ‚Äòto be a man‚Äô portrait series project.

i started this project towards the end of 2018 as a means to challenge the concept of toxic masculinity. the rise of women‚Äôs movements such the #metoo campaign and increasing awareness of mental health issues specific to men has highlighted the prevalence of toxic masculinity all over the world.

toxic masculinity refers to the socially-constructed attitudes that describe the masculine gender role as violent, unemotional, power hungry and sexually aggressive. it restricts the kinds of emotions and characteristics that are socially acceptable boys and men to express. toxic masculinity has become the standard upon which the "real man" is defined, but also by which ones masculinity can be challenged. 
our culture doesn‚Äôt always leave space for men to express inner struggles therefore boys grow up facing a lot of pressure to conform to what society says is ‚Äònormal‚Äô. that said, failure to embrace these ‚Äòmanly‚Äô qualities often renders harsh consequences not only for men themselves but those around him. for example, substance abuse, depression, self-harm, aggressiveness, objectification and violence towards not only women but other men as well, homophobic and transphobic sentiments and so forth. 
my goal with this photo series is not to label men as bad, evil or incapable of change, but show that it is so important to speak up and fight stigma. men too face a great deal of pressure to conform to these idealistic expectations created by a system that has long catered towards patriarchy. 
i by no means claim to be an expert on this subject but i wanted to create a diverse collective of men who believe it‚Äôs okay to possess and express the qualities and characteristics that society says they shouldn‚Äôt. i hope that this will spread and reach the men who are struggling to accept that things like emotional vulnerability and compassion are strengths and not weaknesses.

i will be releasing this project within the next couple weeks so stay tuned to see what men think being a man today should mean. :)

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company ‚Äúweaponised‚Äù the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how users‚Äô preferences for particular brands on social media platforms ‚Äì facebook, in particular ‚Äì were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaign‚Äôs lesser reported ‚Äúweapons of mass destruction‚Äù. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someone‚Äôs personality. a user‚Äôs predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call ‚Äúpopulist political signalling‚Äù. cambridge analytica, which was¬†shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump‚Äôs former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 ‚Äì including cultural preferences such as fashion and music ‚Äì to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
have you been following the buzz regarding r.kelly?  the first episode of a six episode lifetime series called 'surviving r kelly' which includes interviews with a number of r kelly‚Äôs former friends, family members and colleagues, as well as several women who claim that the singer used his power to sexually and physically abuse women and young girls over a number of years.

whether this is true or not, i do not know. what i do know is this behavior is actually pretty common. the entire #metoo movement is created upon it.

as an hr executive, i can tell you it is also common in the international business world. men and women in certain position use their position and power in negative way hurting other people. sometimes is verbally, other times physically or even sexually. especially women are common victims of such people. this must stop!

nothing is worth being treated like this. if you ever encounter something like this, please contact your hr department! every company should have policies and procedures on how to manage this and they can help you get in contact with additional help and assistance.¬† if the hr department is not willing to do anything, go the police. it is absolutely vital for your health, safety and overall wellbeing ( also of others) that this behavior is stopped. companies are more and more speaking up about not allowing this behavior and taking action.  please¬† do not be afraid, it is your right to have a safe workplace!

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
since the universe strategically placed me on a transformative path to heal my deepest inner wounds, i found myself increasingly attracted to #wolves. i always felt they were beautiful animals, but never really pondered their spiritual symbolism... until now. i've always wanted to heal, but never in my wildest dreams knew that the universe would deliver in such a miraculous way. 
over the past decade (particularly 2017-2018), i've had to leave a lot of things behind to gain my own soul. i had often wondered why, but now i am sure there is a bigger purpose.

warrior wolves are often forced to leave the pack to find their own path. while they are extremely loyal to their 'soul tribe,' they are also capable of walking to the beat of their own drum. but, once they've found their 'pack' or soulmates, they remain loyal. their existence is a reminder that the path to self-mastery is a lifelong process, and you don't have to do it alone.

since the universe strategically placed me on a transformative path to heal my deepest inner wounds, i found myself increasingly attracted to #wolves. i always felt they were beautiful animals, but never really pondered their spiritual symbolism... until now. i have always wanted to heal, but never in my wildest dreams knew that the universe would deliver in such a miraculous way. 
over the past decade (particularly 2017-2018), i have had to leave a lot of things behind to gain my own soul. i had often wondered why, but now i am sure there is a bigger purpose.

warrior wolves are often forced to leave the pack to find their own path. while they are extremely loyal to their 'soul tribe,' they are also capable of walking to the beat of their own drum. but, once they've found their 'pack' or soulmates, they remain loyal. their existence is a reminder that the path to self-mastery is a lifelong process, and you do not have to do it alone. 
so if you have to leave your tribe to gain yourself, know you are not alone. you will find othersüê∫üíôüê∫üíô #soultribe #healing #transformation #metoo #healthyboundaries #shamanic #wolves #endtraumastigma #growth #change #wayshower #indigo #powerful #freedom #empower #heforshe #strength #warrior #innerpeace #loyalty #respect #writers #motivation #travel #travelers #healthymind #wellness #divinefeminine #divinemasculine #bossbabe

former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text: rape culture is defined as "a sociological concept for a setting in which rape is pervasive and normalized due to societal attitudes about gender and sexuality". in our society, we promote and even glorify sexual assault and abuse in our music, on the big and small screen, in our literature, and in our everyday actions. females  and males are treated as objects to be conquered, possessed, and harnessed for someone else's sexual gratification. this has created a society that can ignore the obvious predations of an r kelly and those like him. this is why those who operate in his particular cycle of abuse can see their actions as merely doing a job as opposed to actively participating in the sexual abuse, assault, and violence against girls and women. surviving r kelly did not bring to light an isolated set of behaviors exhibited by one man, it highlighted an overarching problem within our society that normalizes the predatory tendencies of many men and women, and how those around them are also content to participate directly and indirectly in the traumatization of those who can't protect themselves. r kelly is indeed the monster we believe him to be, but he also represents an entire population of monsters from all races, religions, and socioeconomic backgrounds that need to be weeded out and stopped. in order to do this, we, as a society, have to change our minds and be honest about exactly what sexual assault and abuse is, be willing to call it out when we see it, and be real clear about who is really at fault when it occurs (and it's certainly not the victim). there are too many kids who are surviving their own monster and they need us to make it stop! text:
"when people think of domestic violence (or intimate partner violence), images of a woman being physically beaten by her male partner come to mind. posters, movies and television shows tend to paint domestic violence in this singular narrative. women are always the victim, men always the perpetrator, and it all comes down to be punched or kicked - at least that‚Äôs what the media tells us.

but there's more to it than that. what if you're unhappy or feel unsafe, but your partner hasn't actually hit you? or what if your partner is the same gender as you or the person who scares you is a woman? does that even count?" read more in my most recent piece here: 
https://www.kinkly.com/is-your-relationship-unhealthy-or-abusive-knowing-when-to-get-help-and-get-out/2/17407

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i am not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it is a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
can i take this opportunity to introduce myself? i‚Äôve seen new faces here and i want to say two things: hello & welcome! my name is ashley. my hope for you is that you will grow in seeing more of your worth each and every day.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
5 years ago i was sexually assaulted. each day following it i had to choose to fight for myself. i learned that being brave doesn't always mean you feel like a roaring lion. sometimes being brave means you are very afraid, but you still take the next step in front of you.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
for the longest time, i thought i would forever feel imprisoned by the pain and the after-effects of what happened. but one day i was able to breathe a little easier. and then, i remember the first time a day had gone by and i didn't think about the assault even one time.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i still have hard days now and then, but i no longer feel imprisoned. fighting for myself not only brought tremendous healing, but it also taught me to truly love and value myself. when you fight for yourself, part of you has to believe deep down that you are worth fighting for.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
regardless of your story, i hope you know that you are worth fighting for. your heart is special and desperately needed. don't let any experience, anyone, and even yourself, tell you otherwise.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i hope your time with me - whether it be here, on the restoring heart podcast, a retreat, or a coaching session - will be an indispensable part of your journey in investing more in yourself - because you are worth it.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
#selflove #selfworth #iamenough #restoringheart #icwlh #worth #selfvalue #selfesteem #metoo #believesurvivors #sexualabuse  #survivor #sexualtrauma #sexualassault
name: ASHLEY BAXTER
tweet_full:
can i take this opportunity to introduce myself? i‚Äôve seen new faces here and i want to say two things: hello & welcome! my name is ashley. my hope for you is that you will grow in seeing more of your worth each and every day.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
5 years ago i was sexually assaulted. each day following it i had to choose to fight for myself. i learned that being brave does not always mean you feel like a roaring lion. sometimes being brave means you are very afraid, but you still take the next step in front of you.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
for the longest time, i thought i would forever feel imprisoned by the pain and the after-effects of what happened. but one day i was able to breathe a little easier. and then, i remember the first time a day had gone by and i didn't think about the assault even one time.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i still have hard days now and then, but i no longer feel imprisoned. fighting for myself not only brought tremendous healing, but it also taught me to truly love and value myself. when you fight for yourself, part of you has to believe deep down that you are worth fighting for.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
regardless of your story, i hope you know that you are worth fighting for. your heart is special and desperately needed. do not let any experience, anyone, and even yourself, tell you otherwise.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i hope your time with me - whether it be here, on the restoring heart podcast, a retreat, or a coaching session - will be an indispensable part of your journey in investing more in yourself - because you are worth it.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

text:
to compartmentalize is a psychological defense mechanism people use to reduce the mental discomfort or anxiety associated with two conflicting values, though, emotions or beliefs that battle within them. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
the goal of compartmentalizing is to reduce cognitive dissonance which is often misused to mean compartmentalization itself. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
cognitive dissonance is the uncomfortable feelings. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
compartmentalization is the act of fighting those feelings through the use of the defense mechanism. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
unfortunately in a community that has largely been built out of the ruins of this country‚Äôs collective trauma  and shame, we are used to two diametrically opposed ideas being present at once thus, we have learned over time to master this defense mechanism. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
as a comedian recently said, ‚Äúif r kelly has been able to exist in this environment for so long that means the environment was predator friendly.‚Äù ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
in an environment where the neighborhood drug dealer could also give out turkeys and bikes during the holiday season, and get your parents strung out on drugs, and a murderer can also be the protector of your family, a cop is also a domestic abuser, your cousin could molest you, where you are taught to fear the law, and embrace criminals. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
the fore founders of this country who were morally bankrupt murders, rapist and enslavers widely celebrated daily. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
where women see a whole man, not claim or take care of their children but they still procreate and are confident he will take care of yours?‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
we have been taught all our lives to take away the good from bad situations. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
there is very little doubt there are people who will still be able to ‚Äúseparate the man from his music.‚Äù because it is who we have been taught to be in this country. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£
just a thought check out our stories for the links to this week's episode of @blacktherapistpodcast‚Å£‚Å£

text:
"you are your own kind of beautiful" 
for as long as i can remember i thought the only way my hair looked beautiful was when it was straight, smooth and ‚Äúprofessional‚Äù looking. growing up in an era where mainstream media only portrayed women with straight hair and blue eyes to be ‚Äúbeautiful‚Äù made it very hard for me to love everything about myself.¬† as well as growing up in a predominately white neighbourhood and going to school where there were only a handful of girls that ‚Äúlooked like me with my kind of hair‚Äù didn‚Äôt make it any easier. even though my mom is super supportive and still to this day encourages me to embrace my hair and love everything about myself, growing up it was hard to do so with so many biases constantly in my face. at some point in childhood we develop this idea where your parents have to tell you positive things about yourself because you are their child. unfortunately overtime with this mind-set their words become less valuable until we hit a level of maturity and realize their opinions are the ones that actually hold the most value, in my case at least.

i still remember my mom‚Äôs famous lines they were ‚Äúbaby your hair is beautiful women pay money to have hair like yours, even men in my day!‚Äù, ‚Äúyou‚Äôre going to ruin your hair and regret it!‚Äù and ‚Äúone day you‚Äôre going to wish you listened to me‚Äù and boy wasn‚Äôt she right‚Ä¶ i wish i listened to her!  from 1999 until about 2010 i straightened my hair on a regular basis to ‚Äúfit in‚Äù and hide my natural, frizzy big curly hair. over those 11 years i had fully damaged my hair it was thin and stringy my curls were absolutely gone. it wasn‚Äôt until 2010 i did a big chop however that still didn‚Äôt help my curls return. in late 2013 i made the decision to truly embody self-love as a part of that journey i started researching how to bring my hair back to its natural state. it wasn‚Äôt a pretty transition, but one that was worth it.

text:
when i need a good cry, when i want to feel inspired, when i need to be reminded about the power of truly owning our gifts, i look up oprah's speech from last year's golden globes.

i hesitated writing this post because i was afraid of being branded an "oprah-believer" but then i realized i was hiding in the shadows from my own truth.

ever since i was young, i looked forward to 4pm when oprah would be on tv. she made me feel good, inspired, alive. sometimes she was over the top but that never got in the way of a deep knowing in me that this woman was chanelling the courage, self-confidence and ambition that i kept under wraps deep within myself.

last year, after watching oprah's speech live, i realized that i was not living my truth. i had wanted to launch my business for years and had been avoiding doing so because of, you guessed it, fear. 
today, i replace fear daily with faith. when i'm tuned in with my intuition, with faith, i know that i can't fail.

as oprah said in her speech: "speaking your truth is the most powerful tool we all have." i now know this to be true, more than ever.

if you feel ready to own your truth in your life and career, i can help you. i offer a free consult to help you get started in living beyond your fear and owning your full success.

text:
on today's derek mansplains it all, after 1 year and 50 episodes, i have my first return guest! i asked sopan deb of the new york times to come by the studio to help me understand perceived media bias, political grandstanding and the meritocracy of stand up comedy!
-
sopan deb is a culture reporter for the new york times, writing about the intersection of politics and culture, among other topics. before joining the times, he covered donald j. trump's presidential campaign for cbs news.
-
his work has previously appeared on nbc, al jazeera america and the boston globe, ranging from examining the trek of endangered manatees to following a class of blind filmmakers in boston led by the former executive producer of "friends."
-
follow sopan on twitter at: @sopandeb and instagram at: @soap07
-

on today's derek mansplains it all, after 1 year and 50 episodes, i have my first return guest! i asked sopan deb of the new york times to come by the studio to help me understand perceived media bias, political grandstanding and the meritocracy of stand up comedy!
-
sopan deb is a culture reporter for the new york times, writing about the intersection of politics and culture, among other topics. before joining the times, he covered donald j. trump's presidential campaign for cbs news.
-
his work has previously appeared on nbc, al jazeera america and the boston globe, ranging from examining the trek of endangered manatees to following a class of blind filmmakers in boston led by the former executive producer of "friends."
-
follow sopan on twitter at: @sopandeb and instagram at: @soap07
-

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin

text:
"panty portrait: poontang" from the panty project, 10 of 51
.

fiber art, archival pigment print on museum cotton rag, 19 x 14 inches .
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: 2017 and 2018 have been a tough couple of years.  the sexual assault that i had  unfortunately experienced while being stationed overseas left me with medical issues, mental health issues (including ptsd), not caring about myself or anyone else, constant drinking to suppress the depression and anxiety, suicidal thoughts and much more. i chose this picture to represent this post as a reminder that i am a strong person and have made incredible improvement on my mentality. this picture shows a woman who is confident, beautiful & fierce. this picture  proves to myself that i can get  back to how i used to be. i‚Äôm so thankful that god brought me to jacksonville, and that he‚Äôs allowing me to stay here. i‚Äôm so thankful for the support system i have down here. 2019 will be my year. don‚Äôt be afraid to speak out and stand up for yourself or others that you may know  who have experienced and unfortunate situation. we are not alone. our voices need to be heard. i‚Äôm not posting this status, to make people  feel bad for me, because things like this happen ...however,i‚Äôm posting the status as a milestone for myself and for the progress that i‚Äôve made since  june 29, 2017. shout out to @amber_marie_22_  for taking this photo. #metoo #sexualassaultawareness #iamstronger

the magazine ranked women's universities based on the alleged willingness of female students to engage in sex while at drinking parties.

text:
finished this book!
book: human sexuality, an all-embracing gift
author: gerald d. coleman, ss
length: 441 pages
published: 1997
my personal reflection:
our sexuality is a beautiful gift. we have been created by love to love. we exist for relationship: relationship with god and others. our sexuality is much more than just having sex, we are sexual beings. as incarnate spirits, as humans with a body-soul dynamic, our sexuality allows us to express who we are and our love. our sexuality is like a language. like any language we learn, discover and integrate it into our lives. true and healthy sexuality allows for true and healthy intimacy. as we have seen recently with the rise of the #metoo movement and the cases of abuse in the church and society, there are people with deep wounds, who lack integration and who can even harm others greatly. these people need to open up right away about their difficulties and get help. the sooner they do, the sooner light will illuminate their darkness. there is a great need for a healthier integration of sexuality in our society. there is a need for a healthier integration of sexuality that creates space for true love and intimacy, which protects freedom, respects the other person and loves them for who they are, not for what they can give me or what i can rob from them. any relationships where violence, manipulation, disrespect, or objectification take place, clearly hurt those involved, cause wounds and need to be brought to the light so that healing may take place. our gender identity, sexual orientation and sexual intention, must be integrated into our lives. there is a risk of separating these aspects of our lives from who we are and present ourselves to be, our integration of them allows us to live and love authentically. our sexuality is a language, so any lack of coherence, lies, duplicity, lack of freedom or lack of fidelity, is a sign that we need help and are yearning for liberation (cf. 66). all of us are wounded by original sin, personal sin and sins in society around us, and some of our tendencies may not always communicate true love, or true intimacy... *continued in comments*... üëá

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
trigger warnings: sexual harassment. 
the only purpose behind this post is to use the platform we have to generate awareness. any unsolicited advise, negativity of any kind, victim shaming, blaming, #notallmen or why didn't you do "xyz" will have you blocked and reported and you'll get a special shoutout on our stories (we all know how much you hate that). its high time we start taking this issue seriously. .
.
.
new year's eve:
it's just 1 hour to midnight on 31st december 2018. we're headed to the cliff of varkala beach for the countdown to start the new year on a high note. 
as we walk towards the cliff, we ( 2 girls 2 guys) get surrounded by crowds of local men closing in on us. they then push our male friends out of the crowd and proceed to put their hands on us without our consent. .
.
.
we had atleast 5 men touching us at a time. they put their hands on our breasts, our crotch, our waist, shoulder, inside our tshirt, spanked us.. left us with bruises on our bodies and only let us go once they were done with us. this complete abuse of our bodies happened in front of more people than i can count including the police, crowds of tourists & women but nobody could say or do anything. it was the two of us and 20 of them. we were not the only ones, this happened to every girl in our hostel. it was like an organised effort to molest women.

you know the worst part in all of this? we weren't even shocked, this happens all the time. all we felt was grateful, because atleast they didn't strip us naked or rape us in public.
and if that's not messed up, if you still believe that this country respects women to the slightest bit, if you think we are safe, if you are not a feminist, if you believe women exaggerate, then you're obviously either an entitled, mysoginistic, sexist, ignorant man or a woman who lives in her own little world and should be ashamed of calling herself one.
in the real world, we are not safe. we are sexually harrassed, assaulted everyday everywhere no matter what we wear or look like.
we don't want you to feel sorry for us. we want you to be angry with us.

lifetimes‚Äôs ‚Äúsurviving  r. kelly‚Äù docuseries aires today. 9/8 central. i‚Äôm certain it took great strength for those survivors  to share  their experiences.  the previews alone have brought  out the ugly in social media.  r. kelly has been muted in my book.  the red flags have already been there. those that choose to continue to support him are nothing more than enablers who cosign the narrative that black women and their pain don‚Äôt matter. .
.
.

according the ‚Äúsexual violence victimization and associations with health in a community sample of african american women‚Äù - a recent study conducted by the national sexual violence resource center, 73% of the women surveyed were under the age of 18 when they experienced  their first unwanted sexual experience and  96% percent of them knew their perpetrator. .
.
.

unlike some, i don‚Äôt need a conviction to know  r. kelly is a pedophile and sexual perpetrator.  his marriage to the then underaged alyiah was a huge red flag. furthermore, the type of support he continues to receive despite the facts, highlights why sexual trauma and violence goes underreported in the black community. some would much rather look the other way because they enjoy the benefits of the perpetrator. .
.
.

one of the worst experiences in life is having to confront your perpetrator. to not have community support or be labled as a liar or trouble maker only adds insult to injury. .
.
.

sending  light, strength, peace and complete healing to those survivors.  #muterkelly #metoo üé•lifetime

text:
thank you @fatimata25 fatima ishiaku for the courage to speak up.
fatima is a #sexualviolence survivor who recalls being raped daily by her step father from age 7 to 14. do you know all the while she thought that was her biological father? and that her mother never believed what she was going through?
.
she has lost her engagement twice, been bullied and shamed by confidants, attempted suicide and stigmatized because she shared her story.
.
fast forward to today she can proudly say she is a survivor but she is concerned about those still not able to break the silence culture. she shares her story in her soon to be published book.
.
awlo will be helping fatima touch more lives, and create a sensitization; for more women to speak up, find the courage to share their story and let this be their stepping stone and not a label. this is fatima's message.
